# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: actium
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:actium/acarnania] Acarnania's foundation in Greek mythology was traditionally ascribed to Acarnan, son of Alcmaeon.
[src:actium/acarnania] The name of Acarnania appears to have been unknown in the earliest times.
[src:actium/acarnania] Homer (8th century BC) only calls the country opposite Ithaca and Cephalonia, under the general name of "Epeirus" (῎ηπειρος), or the mainland, although he frequently mentions the Aetolians.
[src:actium/acarnania] The country is said to have been originally inhabited by the Taphii (or Teleboae), the Leleges, and the Curetes.
[src:actium/acarnania] The Taphii, or Teleboae were chiefly found in the islands off the western coast of Acarnania, where they maintained themselves by piracy.
[src:actium/acarnania] The Leleges were more widely disseminated, and were also in possession at one period of Aetolia, Locris, and other parts of Greece.
[src:actium/acarnania] The Curetes are said to have come from Aetolia, and to have settled in Acarnania, after they had been expelled from the former country by Aetolus and his followers.
[src:actium/acarnania] The name of Acarnania is derived from Acarnan, the son of Alcmaeon, who is said to have settled at the mouth of the Achelous.
[src:actium/acarnania] If this tradition is of any value, it would intimate that an Argive colony settled on the coast of Acarnania at an early period.
[src:actium/acarnania] In the 7th century BC, Greek influence in the region became prominent when Corinth settled Anactorium, Sollium and Leucas, and Kefalonia settled Astacus.
[src:actium/acarnania] The settlements of Alyzeia, Coronta, Limnaea, Medion, Oeniadae, Palaerus, Phoitiai and Stratus are also mentioned by Thucydides, this latter city being the seat of a loose confederation of Acarnanian powers that was maintained until the late 1st century BC.
[src:actium/acarnania] The ancient Acarnanians, however, were Greeks, and as such were allowed to contend in the great Pan-Hellenic games, although they were closely connected with their neighbors, the Agraeans and Amphilochians on the Ambracian Gulf, who were barbarian or non-Hellenic nations.
[src:actium/acarnania] Like other rude mountaineers, the Acarnanians are praised for their fidelity and courage.
[src:actium/acarnania] They formed good light-armed troops, and were excellent slingers.
[src:actium/acarnania] They lived, for the most part, dispersed in villages, retiring, when attacked, to the mountains.
[src:actium/acarnania] Strabo relates that they were united, however, in a political League (the Acarnanian League), of which Aristotle wrote an account in a work now lost (Ἀκαρνάνων Πολιτεία).
[src:actium/acarnania] Thucydides mentions a hill, named Olpae, near the Amphilochian Argos, which the Acarnanians had fortified as a place of judicial meeting for the settlement of disputes.
[src:actium/acarnania] The meetings of the League were usually held at Stratus, which was the chief town in Acarnania; but, in the time of the Romans, the meetings took place either at Thyrium, or at Leucas, the latter of which places became, at that time, the chief city in Acarnania.
[src:actium/acarnania] At an early period, when part of Amphilochia belonged to the Acarnanians, they used to hold a public judicial congress at Olpae, a fortified hill about 3 miles (4.8 km) from Argos Amphilochicum.
[src:actium/acarnania] Of the constitution of their League, we have scarcely any particulars.
[src:actium/acarnania] We learn from an inscription found at Punta, the site of ancient Actium, that there were a council and a general assembly of the people, by which decrees were passed: Ἔδοξε τᾷ βουλᾷ καὶ τῷ κοινῷ τῶν Ἁκαρνάνων.
[src:actium/acarnania] At the head of the League, there was a strategus (Στρατηγός) or general; and the council had a secretary (γραμματεύς), who appears to have been a person of importance, as in the Achaean and Aetolian Leagues.
[src:actium/acarnania] The chief priest (ἱεραπόλος) of the temple of Apollo at Actium seems to have been a person of high rank; and either his name or that of the strategus was employed for official dates, like that of the first Archon at Athens.
[src:actium/acarnania] Because it is located strategically on the maritime route to Italy, Acarnania was involved in many wars.
[src:actium/acarnania] The Acarnanians espoused the cause of the expelled Amphilochians, and in order to obtain the restoration of the latter, they applied for assistance to Athens.
[src:actium/acarnania] The Athenians accordingly sent an expedition under Phormio, who took Argos, expelled the Ambraciots, and restored the town to the Amphilochians and Acarnanians.
[src:actium/acarnania] An alliance was now formally concluded between the Acarnamians and Athenians.
[src:actium/acarnania] The only towns of Acarnania which did not join it were Oeniadae and Astacus.
[src:actium/acarnania] The Acarnanians were of great service in maintaining the supremacy of Athens in the western part of Greece, and they distinguished themselves particularly in 426 BC, when they gained a signal victory under the command of Demosthenes over the Peloponnesians and Ambraciots at the Battle of Olpae.
[src:actium/acarnania] At the conclusion of this campaign they concluded a peace with the Ambraciots, although they still continued allies of Athens.
[src:actium/acarnania] In 391 BC we find the Acarnanians engaged in war with the Achaeans, who had taken possession of Calydon in Aetolia; and as the latter were hard-pressed by the Acarnanians, they applied for aid to the Lacedaemonians (Spartans), who sent an army into Acarnania, commanded by King Agesilaus.
[src:actium/acarnania] The latter ravaged the country, but his expedition was not attended with any lasting consequences, whilst the cities of Acarnania surrendered to the Lacedaemonians under Agesilaus, and continued to be Spartan allies for a time, they joined the Second Athenian League in 375 BC.
[src:actium/acarnania] The Acarnanians later sided with the Boeotians in their fight against Sparta, and with Athens against Philip II of Macedon at Chaeronea.
[src:actium/acarnania] After the time of Alexander the Great, in 314 BC, at the behest of the Macedonian king Cassander, the settlements of Acarnania lying near the Aetolian border were conglomerated into fewer, larger settlements.
[src:actium/acarnania] Still, border conflicts with the Aetolians were frequent, and led to Acarnania's territory being partitioned between Aetolia and Epirus in, c.
[src:actium/acarnania] After the fall of the king of Epirus, the Acarnanian territory that had been given to Epirus regained its independence, and Leucas became the capital of the region, but conflict with the Aetolians remained.
[src:actium/acarnania] The Acarnanians in consequence united themselves closely to the Macedonian kings, to whom they remained faithful in their various vicissitudes of fortune.
[src:actium/acarnania] They refused to desert the cause of Philip in his war with the Romans, and it was not till after the capture of Leucas, their principal town, and the defeat of Philip at the Battle of Cynoscephalae that they submitted to Rome.
[src:actium/acarnania] When Antiochus III king of Syria, invaded Greece, 191 BC, the Acarnanians were persuaded by their countryman Mnasilochus to espouse his cause; but on the expulsion of Antiochus from Greece, they came again under the supremacy of Rome.
[src:actium/acarnania] In the settlement of the affairs of Greece by Aemilius Paulus and the Roman commissioners after the defeat of Perseus (168 BC), Leucas was separated from Acarnania, and the city of Thyrreion was appointed the new capital.
[src:actium/acarnania] In the 1st century BC, Acarnania suffered greatly at the hands of pirates, and in Roman civil wars.
[src:actium/acarnania] When Greece was reduced to the form of a Roman province, it is doubtful whether Acarnania was annexed to the province of Achaea or of Epirus, but it is mentioned at a later time as part of Epirus.
[src:actium/acarnania] The inhabitants of several of its towns were removed by Augustus to Nicopolis, which he founded after the Battle of Actium, and Acarnania fell under that city's rule; and in the time of Augustus emperor the country is described by Strabo as utterly worn out and exhausted.
[src:actium/acarnania] In 395, it became part of the Eastern Roman Empire.
[src:actium/acarnania] When the empire was attacked by Western powers in the Fourth Crusade (1204), Acarnania passed to the Despotate of Epirus and in 1348 it was conquered by Serbia.
[src:actium/acarnania] Then in 1480 it fell to the Ottoman Empire.
[src:actium/acarnania] Acarnania is composed of three main regions: 1) a rocky coastline, 2) a rugged strip of mountain range that follows the coastline, and 3) plains lying between these mountains and the Achelous River.
[src:actium/acarnania] Anciently, Acarnania was reckoned the most westerly province of Greece, bounded on the north by the Ambracian Gulf, on the northeast by Amphilochia, on the west and southwest by the Ionian Sea, and on the east by Aetolia.
[src:actium/acarnania] It contained about 1,571 square miles (4,070 km2).
[src:actium/acarnania] Under the Romans, or probably a little earlier, the river Achelous formed the boundary between Acarnania and Aetolia; but in the time of the Peloponnesian War, the territory of Oeniadae, which was one of the Acarnanian towns, extended east of this river.
[src:actium/acarnania] The interior of Acarnania was covered with forests and mountains of no great elevation.
[src:actium/acarnania] Between these mountains there are several lakes, and many fertile valleys.
[src:actium/acarnania] The chief river of the country is the Achelous, which in the lower part of its course flows through a vast plain of great natural fertility, called after itself the Paracheloitis.
[src:actium/acarnania] By the 19th century, the plain was covered with marshes, and the greater part of it appeared to have been formed by the alluvial depositions of the Achelous.
[src:actium/acarnania] Owing to this circumstance, and to the river having frequently altered its channel, the southern part of the coast of Acarnania has undergone numerous changes since antiquity.
[src:actium/acarnania] The chief affluent of the Achelous in Acarnania is the Anapus (Ἄναπος), which flowed into the main stream 80 stadia south of Stratus.
[src:actium/acarnania] There are several promontories on the coast, but of these only two are especially named by writers in antiquity, the promontory of Actium and that of Crithote (Κριθωτή), on the west coast, forming one side of the small bay, on which the town of Astacus stood.
[src:actium/acarnania] Of the inland lakes, the only one mentioned by name by the classical writers is that of Melite (Μελίτη; the modern Lake Trichonida), 30 stadia long and 20 broad, north of the mouth of the Achelous, in the territory of Oeniadae.
[src:actium/acarnania] There was a lagoon, or salt lake, between Leucas and the Ambracian gulf, to which Strabo gives the name of Myrtuntium (Μυρτούντιον).
[src:actium/acarnania] Although the soil of Acarnania was fertile, it was not much cultivated by the inhabitants.
[src:actium/acarnania] The products of the country are rarely mentioned by the ancient writers.
[src:actium/acarnania] Pliny speaks of iron mines, and also of a pearl-fishery off Actium.
[src:actium/acarnania] The chief wealth of the inhabitants consisted in their herds and flocks, which pastured in the rich meadows in the lower part of the Achelous.
[src:actium/acarnania] There were numerous islands off the western coast of Acarnania.
[src:actium/actia] Actia were also celebrated at the same time at Rome by the orders of the senate and were also celebrated in other parts of the Roman empire.
[src:actium/actia] This ancient stadium was located in the so-called 'Proasteion' (sacred grove) of the Graeco-Roman city of Nikopolis.
[src:actium/actia] Together with the nearby gymnasium, theatre and hippodrome it was the location of the famous Actian Games.
[src:actium/actia] These games, which featured athletic, equestrian and musical events, were first held in 27 BC to celebrate the victory of the first Roman emperor Augustus over his adversaries, Marc Antony and his Egyptian wife Cleopatra.
[src:actium/actia] They were held every four years up to the mid-3rd century AD.
[src:actium/actia] Dating from just after the city's foundation, the ancient stadium of Nikopolis has two semicircular ends (*sphendones*), typical of the amphitheatre type that was in use during the first 200 years of the principate.
[src:actium/actia] The stadiums of ancient Laodikeia (near Pamukkale, Turkey) and Aphrodisias (Geyre, Turkey) have a similar architecture.
[src:actium/actia] The north side of the stadium, which must have held a capacity of at least 10,000 spectators, was built on the side of a hill, while artificial deposits were used for the other sides.
[src:actium/actia] The walls were made of a rubble core faced with several courses of bricks.
[src:actium/actia] On the west side of the stadium were three apsidal entrances leading to the gymnasium, the central one larger than the others.
[src:actium/actia] The entrances in the *sphendone* at the east led to the theatre nearby.
[src:actium/actia] Locals call this stadium *to karavi*, meaning 'the ship', which of course relates to the structure's shape.
[src:actium/actia] Archaeological investigations are still regularly undertaken in and around the stadium today.
[src:actium/actinium] A soft, silvery-white radioactive metal, actinium reacts rapidly with oxygen and moisture in air, forming a white coating of actinium oxide that prevents further oxidation.
[src:actium/actinium] As with most lanthanides and many actinides, actinium assumes oxidation state +3 in nearly all its chemical compounds.
[src:actium/actinium] Actinium is found only in traces in uranium and thorium ores as the isotope 227Ac, which decays with a half-life of 21.772 years, predominantly emitting beta and sometimes alpha particles, and 228Ac, which is beta active with a half-life of 6.15 hours.
[src:actium/actinium] One tonne of natural uranium in ore contains about 0.2 milligrams of actinium-227, and one tonne of thorium contains about 5 nanograms of actinium-228.
[src:actium/actinium] The close similarity of physical and chemical properties of actinium and lanthanum makes the separation of actinium from the ore impractical.
[src:actium/actinium] Instead, the element is prepared, in milligram amounts, by the neutron irradiation of 226Ra in a nuclear reactor.
[src:actium/actinium] Owing to its scarcity, high price, and radioactivity, actinium has no significant industrial use.
[src:actium/actinium] Its current applications include a neutron source and an agent for radiation therapy.
[src:actium/actinium] André-Louis Debierne, a French chemist, announced the discovery of a new element in 1899.
[src:actium/actinium] He separated it from pitchblende residues left by Marie and Pierre Curie after they had extracted radium.
[src:actium/actinium] In 1899, Debierne described the substance as similar to titanium and (in 1900) as similar to thorium.
[src:actium/actinium] Friedrich Oskar Giesel found in 1902 a substance similar to lanthanum and called it "emanium" in 1904.
[src:actium/actinium] Articles published in the 1970s and later suggest that Debierne's results published in 1904 conflict with those reported in 1899 and 1900.
[src:actium/actinium] This has led some authors to advocate that Giesel alone should be credited with the discovery.
[src:actium/actinium] A less confrontational vision of scientific discovery is proposed by Adloff.
[src:actium/actinium] He suggests that hindsight criticism of the early publications should be mitigated by the then nascent state of radiochemistry: highlighting the prudence of Debierne's claims in the original papers, he notes that nobody can contend that Debierne's substance did not contain actinium.
[src:actium/actinium] Debierne, who is now considered by the vast majority of historians as the discoverer, lost interest in the element and left the topic.
[src:actium/actinium] Giesel, on the other hand, can rightfully be credited with the first preparation of radiochemically pure actinium and with the identification of its atomic number 89.
[src:actium/actinium] The name actinium originates from the Ancient Greek *aktis, aktinos* (ακτίς, ακτίνος), meaning beam or ray.
[src:actium/actinium] Its symbol Ac is also used in abbreviations of other compounds that have nothing to do with actinium, such as acetyl, acetate and sometimes acetaldehyde.
[src:actium/actinium] Actinium is a soft, silvery-white, radioactive, metallic element.
[src:actium/actinium] Its estimated shear modulus is similar to that of lead.
[src:actium/actinium] Owing to its strong radioactivity, actinium glows in the dark with a pale blue light, which originates from the surrounding air ionized by the emitted energetic particles.
[src:actium/actinium] Actinium has similar chemical properties to lanthanum and other lanthanides, and therefore these elements are difficult to separate when extracting from uranium ores.
[src:actium/actinium] Solvent extraction and ion chromatography are commonly used for the separation.
[src:actium/actinium] The first element of the actinides, actinium, gave the set its name, much as lanthanum had done for the lanthanides.
[src:actium/actinium] The actinides are much more diverse than the lanthanides and therefore it was not until 1945 that the most significant change to Dmitri Mendeleev's periodic table since the recognition of the lanthanides, the introduction of the actinides, was generally accepted after Glenn T.
[src:actium/actinium] Seaborg's research on the transuranium elements (although it had been proposed as early as 1892 by British chemist Henry Bassett).
[src:actium/actinium] Actinium reacts rapidly with oxygen and moisture in air, forming a white coating of actinium oxide that impedes further oxidation.
[src:actium/actinium] As with most lanthanides and actinides, actinium exists in the oxidation state +3, and the Ac3+ ions are colorless in solutions.
[src:actium/actinium] The oxidation state +3 originates from the [Rn] 6d17s2 electronic configuration of actinium, with three valence electrons that are easily donated to give the stable closed-shell structure of the noble gas radon.
[src:actium/actinium] Although the 5f orbitals are unoccupied in an actinium atom, it can be used as a valence orbital in actinium complexes and hence it is generally considered the first 5f element by authors working on it.
[src:actium/actinium] Ac3+ is the largest of all known tripositive ions and its first coordination sphere contains approximately 10.9 ± 0.5 water molecules.
[src:actium/actinium] Due to actinium's intense radioactivity, only a limited number of actinium compounds are known.
[src:actium/actinium] These include: AcF3, AcCl3, AcBr3, AcOF, AcOCl, AcOBr, Ac2S3, Ac2O3, AcPO4 and Ac(NO3)3.
[src:actium/actinium] They all contain actinium in the oxidation state +3.
[src:actium/actinium] In particular, the lattice constants of the analogous lanthanum and actinium compounds differ by only a few percent.
[src:actium/actinium] Here *a*, *b* and *c* are lattice constants, No is the space group number, and *Z* is the number of formula units per unit cell.
[src:actium/actinium] Density was not measured directly but calculated from the lattice parameters.
[src:actium/actinium] Actinium oxide (Ac2O3) can be obtained by heating the hydroxide at 500 °C (932 °F) or the oxalate at 1,100 °C (2,010 °F), in vacuum.
[src:actium/actinium] Its crystal lattice is isotypic with the oxides of most trivalent rare-earth metals.
[src:actium/actinium] Actinium trifluoride can be produced either in solution or in solid reaction.
[src:actium/actinium] The former reaction is carried out at room temperature, by adding hydrofluoric acid to a solution containing actinium ions.
[src:actium/actinium] In the latter method, actinium metal is treated with hydrogen fluoride vapors at 700 °C (1,292 °F) in an all-platinum setup.
[src:actium/actinium] Treating actinium trifluoride with ammonium hydroxide at 900–1,000 °C (1,650–1,830 °F) yields oxyfluoride AcOF.
[src:actium/actinium] Whereas lanthanum oxyfluoride can be easily obtained by burning lanthanum trifluoride in air at 800 °C (1,470 °F) for an hour, similar treatment of actinium trifluoride yields no AcOF and only results in melting of the initial product.
[src:actium/actinium] Actinium trichloride is obtained by reacting actinium hydroxide or oxalate with carbon tetrachloride vapors at temperatures above 960 °C (1,760 °F).
[src:actium/actinium] Similarly to the oxyfluoride, actinium oxychloride can be prepared by hydrolyzing actinium trichloride with ammonium hydroxide at 1,000 °C (1,830 °F).
[src:actium/actinium] However, in contrast to the oxyfluoride, the oxychloride could well be synthesized by igniting a solution of actinium trichloride in hydrochloric acid with ammonia.
[src:actium/actinium] and treating it with ammonium hydroxide at 500 °C (932 °F) results in the oxybromide AcOBr.
[src:actium/actinium] Actinium hydride was obtained by reduction of actinium trichloride with potassium at 300 °C (572 °F), and its structure was deduced by analogy with the corresponding LaH2 hydride.
[src:actium/actinium] The source of hydrogen in the reaction was uncertain.
[src:actium/actinium] Mixing monosodium phosphate (NaH2PO4) with a solution of actinium in hydrochloric acid yields white-colored actinium phosphate hemihydrate (AcPO4·0.5H2O), and heating actinium oxalate with hydrogen sulfide vapors at 1,400 °C (2,550 °F) for a few minutes results in a black actinium sulfide Ac2S3.
[src:actium/actinium] It may be produced by acting with a mixture of hydrogen sulfide and carbon disulfide on actinium oxide at 1,000 °C (1,830 °F).
[src:actium/actinium] Naturally occurring actinium is principally composed of two radioactive isotopes; 227Ac (from the radioactive family of 235U) and 228Ac (a granddaughter of 232Th).
[src:actium/actinium] 227Ac decays mainly as a beta emitter with a very small energy, but in 1.38% of cases it emits an alpha particle, so it can readily be identified through alpha spectrometry.
[src:actium/actinium] Thirty-three radioisotopes have been identified, the most stable being 227Ac with a half-life of 21.772 years, 225Ac with a half-life of 10.0 days and 226Ac with a half-life of 29.37 hours.
[src:actium/actinium] All remaining radioactive isotopes have half-lives that are less than 10 hours, and the majority of them have half-lives shorter than one minute.
[src:actium/actinium] The shortest-lived known isotope of actinium is 217Ac (half-life of 69 nanoseconds) which decays through alpha decay.
[src:actium/actinium] Actinium also has two known meta states.
[src:actium/actinium] The most significant isotopes for chemistry are 225Ac, 227Ac, and 228Ac.
[src:actium/actinium] Purified 227Ac comes into equilibrium with its decay products after about a half-year.
[src:actium/actinium] It decays according to its 21.772-year half-life, emitting mostly beta (98.62%) and some alpha particles (1.38%); the successive decay products are part of the actinium series.
[src:actium/actinium] Owing to the low available amounts, low energy of its beta particles (maximum 44.8 keV) and low intensity of alpha radiation, 227Ac is difficult to detect directly by its emission, and it is therefore traced via its decay products.
[src:actium/actinium] The isotopes of actinium range in atomic weight from 203 Da (203Ac) to 236 Da (236Ac).
[src:actium/actinium] Actinium is found only in traces in uranium ores – one tonne of uranium in ore contains about 0.2 milligrams of 227Ac – and in thorium ores, which contain about 5 nanograms of 228Ac per one tonne of thorium.
[src:actium/actinium] The actinium isotope 227Ac is a transient member of the uranium-actinium series decay chain, which begins with the parent isotope 235U (or 239Pu) and ends with the stable lead isotope 207Pb.
[src:actium/actinium] The isotope 228Ac is a transient member of the thorium series decay chain, which begins with the parent isotope 232Th and ends with the stable lead isotope 208Pb.
[src:actium/actinium] The low natural concentration and the close similarity of physical and chemical properties to those of lanthanum and other lanthanides, which are always abundant in actinium-bearing ores, render separation of actinium from the ore impractical.
[src:actium/actinium] The most concentrated actinium sample prepared from raw material consisted of 7 micrograms of 227Ac in less than 0.1 milligrams of La2O3, and complete separation was never achieved.
[src:actium/actinium] Instead, actinium is prepared, in milligram amounts, by the neutron irradiation of 226Ra in a nuclear reactor.
[src:actium/actinium] The reaction yield is about 2% of the radium weight.
[src:actium/actinium] 227Ac can further capture neutrons resulting in small amounts of 228Ac.
[src:actium/actinium] After the synthesis, actinium is separated from radium and from the products of decay and nuclear fusion, such as thorium, polonium, lead, and bismuth.
[src:actium/actinium] The extraction can be performed with thenoyltrifluoroacetone-benzene solution from an aqueous solution of the radiation products, and the selectivity to a certain element is achieved by adjusting the pH (to about 6.0 for actinium).
[src:actium/actinium] An alternative procedure is anion exchange with an appropriate resin in nitric acid, which can result in a separation factor of 1,000,000 for radium and actinium vs. thorium in a two-stage process.
[src:actium/actinium] Actinium can then be separated from radium, with a ratio of about 100, using a low cross-linking cation exchange resin and nitric acid as eluant.
[src:actium/actinium] 225Ac was first produced artificially at the Institute for Transuranium Elements (ITU) in Germany using a cyclotron and at St George Hospital in Sydney using a linac in 2000.
[src:actium/actinium] This rare isotope has potential applications in radiation therapy and is most efficiently produced by bombarding a radium-226 target with 20–30 MeV deuterium ions.
[src:actium/actinium] This reaction also yields 226Ac which however decays with a half-life of 29 hours and thus does not contaminate 225Ac.
[src:actium/actinium] Actinium metal has been prepared by the reduction of actinium fluoride with lithium vapor in vacuum at a temperature between 1,100 and 1,300 °C (2,010 and 2,370 °F).
[src:actium/actinium] Higher temperatures resulted in evaporation of the product, and lower temperatures led to an incomplete transformation.
[src:actium/actinium] Lithium was chosen among other alkali metals because its fluoride is the most volatile.
[src:actium/actinium] Owing to its scarcity, high price and radioactivity, 227Ac currently has no significant industrial use, but 225Ac is currently being studied for use in cancer treatments such as targeted alpha therapies.
[src:actium/actinium] 227Ac is highly radioactive and was therefore studied for use as an active element of radioisotope thermoelectric generators, for example, in spacecraft.
[src:actium/actinium] The oxide of 227Ac pressed with beryllium is also an efficient neutron source with the activity exceeding that of the standard americium-beryllium and radium-beryllium pairs.
[src:actium/actinium] In all those applications, 227Ac (a beta source) is merely a progenitor which generates alpha-emitting isotopes upon its decay.
[src:actium/actinium] The 227AcBe neutron sources can be applied in a neutron probe – a standard device for measuring the quantity of water present in soil, as well as moisture/density for quality control in highway construction.
[src:actium/actinium] Such probes are also used in well logging applications, in neutron radiography, tomography, and other radiochemical investigations.
[src:actium/actinium] 225Ac is applied in medicine to produce 213Bi in a reusable generator or can be used alone as an agent for radiation therapy, in particular targeted alpha therapy (TAT).
[src:actium/actinium] This isotope has a half-life of 10 days, making it much more suitable for radiation therapy than 213Bi (half-life 46 minutes).
[src:actium/actinium] Additionally, 225Ac decays to nontoxic 209Bi rather than toxic lead, which is the final product in the decay chains of several other candidate isotopes, namely 227Th, 228Th, and 230U.
[src:actium/actinium] Not only 225Ac itself, but also its daughters, emit alpha particles which kill cancer cells in the body.
[src:actium/actinium] The major difficulty with the application of 225Ac was that intravenous injection of simple actinium complexes resulted in their accumulation in the bones and liver for a period of tens of years.
[src:actium/actinium] As a result, after the cancer cells were quickly killed by alpha particles from 225Ac, the radiation from the actinium and its daughters might induce new mutations.
[src:actium/actinium] To solve this problem, 225Ac was bound to a chelating agent, such as citrate, ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid (EDTA) or diethylene triamine pentaacetic acid (DTPA).
[src:actium/actinium] This reduced actinium accumulation in the bones, but the excretion from the body remained slow.
[src:actium/actinium] Much better results were obtained with such chelating agents as HEHA (1,4,7,10,13,16-hexaazacyclohexadecane-N,N′,N″,N‴,N‴′,N‴″-hexaacetic acid) or DOTA (1,4,7,10-tetraazacyclododecane-1,4,7,10-tetraacetic acid) coupled to trastuzumab, a monoclonal antibody that interferes with the HER2/neu receptor.
[src:actium/actinium] The latter delivery combination was tested on mice and proved to be effective against leukemia, lymphoma, breast, ovarian, neuroblastoma and prostate cancers.
[src:actium/actinium] The medium half-life of 227Ac (21.77 years) makes it a very convenient radioactive isotope in modeling the slow vertical mixing of oceanic waters.
[src:actium/actinium] The associated processes cannot be studied with the required accuracy by direct measurements of current velocities (of the order 50 meters per year).
[src:actium/actinium] However, evaluation of the concentration depth profiles for different isotopes allows estimating the mixing rates.
[src:actium/actinium] The physics behind this method is as follows: oceanic waters contain homogeneously dispersed 235U.
[src:actium/actinium] Its decay product, 231Pa, gradually precipitates to the bottom, so that its concentration first increases with depth and then stays nearly constant.
[src:actium/actinium] 231Pa decays to 227Ac; however, the concentration of the latter isotope does not follow the 231Pa depth profile, but instead increases toward the sea bottom.
[src:actium/actinium] This occurs because of the mixing processes, which raise some additional 227Ac from the sea bottom.
[src:actium/actinium] Thus, analysis of both 231Pa and 227Ac depth profiles allows researchers to model the mixing behavior.
[src:actium/actinium] There are theoretical predictions that AcHx hydrides (in this case with very high pressure) are a candidate for a near room-temperature superconductor as they have Tc significantly higher than H3S, possibly near 250 K.
[src:actium/actinium] 227Ac is highly radioactive and experiments with it are carried out in a specially designed laboratory equipped with a tight glove box.
[src:actium/actinium] When actinium trichloride is administered intravenously to rats, about 33% of actinium is deposited into the bones and 50% into the liver.
[src:actium/actinium] Its toxicity is comparable to, but slightly lower than, that of americium and plutonium.
[src:actium/actinium] For trace quantities, fume hoods with good aeration suffice; for gram amounts, hot cells with shielding from the intense gamma radiation emitted by 227Ac are necessary.
[src:actium/actium] Actium belonged originally to the Corinthian colonists of Anactorium, who probably founded the sanctuary of Apollo Actius.
[src:actium/actium] In the 3rd century BC it fell to the Acarnanians, who subsequently held their religious summits there.
[src:actium/actium] There was also an ancient festival named Actia, celebrated here in honour of the god.
[src:actium/actium] Augustus after his victory enlarged the temple, and revived the ancient festival, which was henceforth celebrated once in five years (πενταετηρίς, ludi quinquennales), with musical and gymnastic contests, and horse races.
[src:actium/actium] We learn from a Greek inscription found on the site of Actium, and which is probably prior to the time of Augustus, that the chief priest of the temple was called Ἱεραπόλος, and that his name was employed in official documents, like that of the first Archon at Athens, to mark the date.
[src:actium/actium] Strabo says that the temple was situated on an eminence, and that below was a plain with a grove of trees, and a dock-yard; and in another passage he describes the harbour as situated outside of the gulf.
[src:actium/actium] On the opposite coast of Epirus, Augustus founded the city of Nicopolis in honour of his victory.
[src:actium/actium] After the foundation of Nicopolis, a few buildings sprang up around the temple, and it served as a kind of suburb to Nicopolis.
[src:actium/actium] On October 8, 1980, the Greek Ministry of Transport and Communications reported that shipwrecks from the Battle of Actium had been located at Actium near the entrance to the Ambracan Gulf.
[src:actium/actium] In Summer 2009, archaeologists discovered the ruins of the Temple of Apollo and found two statue heads, one of Apollo, one of Artemis (Diana).
[src:actium/actium] The peninsula is connected via an underwater tunnel to the city of Preveza in Epirus, on the opposite side of the mouth of the Ambracian Gulf.
[src:actium/actium] The total length of the tunnel is 1,570 metres (5,150 ft), of which 909 metres (2,982 ft) are located underwater.
[src:actium/aktio-preveza-undersea-tunnel] The **Aktio–Preveza Undersea Tunnel** (Greek: Υποθαλάσσια σήραγγα Πρέβεζας–Ακτίου) is an undersea road tunnel across the mouth of the Ambracian Gulf in western Greece.
[src:actium/aktio-preveza-undersea-tunnel] It links Epirus and the city of Preveza on the north shore of the gulf with the cape of Aktio (Actium) in Aetolia-Acarnania, in Central Greece.
[src:actium/aktio-preveza-undersea-tunnel] Completed in 2002, the tunnel is an important piece of infrastructure in an underdeveloped region, and greatly shortens the travel distance between the two sides of the gulf, which had been only possible by ferry.
[src:actium/aktio-preveza-undersea-tunnel] It is the only undersea tunnel in Greece.
[src:actium/aktio-preveza-undersea-tunnel] The tunnel has a cross-section height of 8.6 metres and width 12.6 metres.
[src:actium/aktio-preveza-undersea-tunnel] The clearance width is 10.6 metres and clearance height is 5.4 metres.
[src:actium/aktio-preveza-undersea-tunnel] The tunnel has a single two-way carriageway and includes a 4.0 metre-wide side lane and a 1.3 metre wide pedestrian sidewalk in each direction.
[src:actium/aktio-preveza-undersea-tunnel] Construction of the tunnel was a joint venture between Christiani & Nielsen and the Athens-based Technical Company of General Construction (TCGC).
[src:actium/aktio-preveza-undersea-tunnel] The architects of the tunnel were the Copenhagen-based Comar Engineers A/S, and Doxiadis & Zannis of Athens.
[src:actium/aktio-preveza-undersea-tunnel] The contracts was awarded in 1995, and construction was turned over to the Greek Ministry of the Environment, Physical Planning and Public Works in 1999.
[src:actium/aktio-preveza-undersea-tunnel] The tunnel is built in an area of severe seismic activity featuring complex geo-technical conditions.
[src:actium/aktio-preveza-undersea-tunnel] As a result, the tunnel contains a number of advanced features, such as stone columns underneath the tunnel to help it withstand soil liquefaction during an earthquake.
[src:actium/aktio-preveza-undersea-tunnel] The total construction cost was approximately 90 million euros.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] The **Ambracian Gulf**, also known as the **Gulf of Arta** or the **Gulf of Actium**, and in some official documents as the **Amvrakikos Gulf** (Greek: Αμβρακικός κόλπος, romanized: *Amvrakikos kolpos*), is a gulf of the Ionian Sea in northwestern Greece.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] About 40 km (25 mi) long and 15 km (9 mi) wide, it is one of the largest enclosed gulfs in Greece, and due to its ecological importance is one of the National Parks of Greece.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] The towns of Preveza, Amphilochia (formerly Karvassaras), and Vonitsa lie on its shores.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] The gulf takes its name from the ancient city of Ambracia located near its shores.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] Its alternative name comes from the medieval (and modern) city of Arta, located in the same place as ancient Ambracia.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] The entrance to the gulf is through a 700 m (2,297 ft)-wide channel between Aktio (ancient Actium) on the south and Preveza on the north; a recent road tunnel connects the two.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] The gulf is quite shallow, and its northern shore is broken by numerous marshes, large parts of which form an estuary system.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] The Louros and Arachthos (or Arta) rivers drain into it; for this reason it is warmer and less salty than the Ionian, and a current flows from the gulf into the sea.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] It is rich in grey mullet, sole, and eel, and is also very famous for the local variety of large shrimp (gabari, in Greek γάμπαρη).
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] It is home to Melibe viridis, a species of sea slug, a nudibranch, a marine gastropod mollusk in the family Tethydidae.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] Sea turtles and dolphins regularly make an appearance, while it contains lagoons very important for birds, attracting among others pelicans and flamingoes.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] The Ambracian Gulf was the site of the Battle of Actium, in which Augustus' forces defeated those of Mark Antony and Cleopatra.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] Battle of Preveza, which Ottoman admiral Hayreddin Barbarossa defeated the Holy League's admiral Andrea Doria, held on the very same gulf in 1538 .
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] From Greek independence (Treaty of Constantinople, 1832) until the Second Balkan War (Treaty of Bucharest, 1913), the gulf formed part of the border between the Kingdom of Greece and the Ottoman Empire.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] The remains of numerous ancient cities lie on its shores: Nicopolis, Argos Ippatum, Limnaea, Preveza and Olpae.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] Since 2002, the northern and southern sides at the mouth of the gulf are connected by the Aktio-Preveza Undersea Tunnel.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] The tunnel greatly shortens the travel distance across the gulf, which used to be possible only by ferry.
[src:actium/ambracian-gulf] The Aktion International Airport (airport code PVK) is built near the Gulf's entrance and serves the region.
[src:actium/anactorium] It was colonized jointly by the Corinthians and Corcyraeans; but in the war between these peoples, in 432 BCE, the Corinthians obtained sole possession of the place by fraud.
[src:actium/anactorium] It remained in the hands of the Corinthians till 425 BCE, when it was taken by the Acarnanians with the assistance of the Athenians, and the Corinthian settlers were expelled.
[src:actium/anactorium] Augustus removed its inhabitants to the town of Nicopolis, which he founded on the opposite coast of Epirus, and Strabo describes it as an emporium of the latter city.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] For Christians, Corinth is well known from the two letters from Paul the Apostle in the New Testament, the First Epistle to the Corinthians and the Second Epistle to the Corinthians.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Corinth is also mentioned in the Acts of the Apostles as part of Paul the Apostle's missionary travels.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In addition, the second book of Pausanias' *Description of Greece* is devoted to Corinth.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Ancient Corinth was one of the largest and most important cities of Greece, with a population of 90,000 in 400 BC.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Romans demolished Corinth in 146 BC after they captured it as result of the Battle of Corinth, built a new city in its place in 44 BC, and later made it the provincial capital of Achaea.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The geophysical situation at Corinth is in many ways ideal for human habitation.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The city is situated on two large geomorphic terraces, at the southern edge of which is located both arable plains and a number of natural springs.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] These abundant sources of fresh water are further supplemented by seasonal rivers descending from the Ayios Vasilios valley and Mount Ziria.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Natural drainage patterns in the region have formed a broad valley, enabling the movement of wheeled and pedestrian traffic between the terraces.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The geological makeup of Corinth provided the basic materials for the city's construction.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The oolitic limestone of the region’s marine sand bars was used extensively in both domestic and public architecture, and local Corinthian stone was quarried extensively and traded widely across the Aegean.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Supplementing this resource are abundant local deposits of calcareous marl, which served as a rich source for the production of ceramics.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] These marls, when dug, dried, powdered, heated, and mixed with water, made for a highly workable clay, excellent for the production of lightweight ceramic vessels.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Pottery created from Corinthian limestone concrete was exported widely in various periods.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Neolithic pottery suggests that the site of Corinth was occupied from at least as early as 6500 BC, and continually occupied into the Early Bronze Age, when, it has been suggested, the settlement acted as a centre of trade.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] However, there is a huge drop in ceramic remains during the Early Helladic II phase and only sparse ceramic remains in the EHIII and MH phases; thus, it appears that the area was very sparsely inhabited in the period immediately before the Mycenaean period.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] There was a settlement on the coast near Lechaion which traded across the Corinthian Gulf; the site of Corinth itself was likely not heavily occupied again until around 900 BC, when it is believed that the Dorians settled there.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Early Helladic II and Early Helladic III eras are listed above.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] According to Corinthian myth as reported by Pausanias, the city was founded by Corinthos, a descendant of the god Zeus.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] However, other myths hold that it was founded by the goddess Ephyra, a daughter of the Titan Oceanus, thus the ancient name of the city (also Ephyra).
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] It seems likely that Corinth was also the site of a Bronze Age Mycenaean palace-city, like Mycenae, Tiryns, or Pylos.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] According to myth, Sisyphus was the founder of a race of ancient kings at Corinth.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] It was also in Corinth that Jason, the leader of the Argonauts, abandoned Medea.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Catalogue of Ships in the Iliad lists the Corinthians amid the contingent fighting in the Trojan War under the leadership of Agamemnon.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In a Corinthian myth recounted to Pausanias in the 2nd century AD, Briareus, one of the Hecatonchires, was the arbitrator in a dispute between Poseidon and Helios, respectively gods of the sea and the sun.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] His verdict was that the Isthmus of Corinth, the area closest to the sea, belonged to Poseidon, and the acropolis of Corinth (Acrocorinth), closest to the sky, belonged to Helios.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Upper Peirene spring is located within the walls of the acropolis.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Pausanias (2.5.1) says that it was put there by Asopus, repaying Sisyphus for information about the abduction of Aegina by Zeus.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] According to legend, the winged horse Pegasus drank at the spring, and was captured and tamed by the Corinthian hero Bellerophon.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Corinth had been a backwater in Greece in the 8th century BC.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Bacchiadae (Βακχιάδαι, *Bakkhiádai*) were a tightly-knit Doric clan and the ruling kinship group of archaic Corinth in the 8th and 7th centuries BC, a period of expanding Corinthian cultural power.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 747 BC (a traditional date), an aristocracy ousted the Bacchiadai Prytaneis and reinstituted the kingship, about the time the Kingdom of Lydia (the endonymic *Basileia Sfard*) was at its greatest, coinciding with the ascent of Basileus Meles, King of Lydia.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Bacchiadae, numbering perhaps a couple of hundred adult males, took power from the last king Telestes (from the House of Sisyphos) in Corinth.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Bacchiads dispensed with kingship and ruled as a group, governing the city by annually electing a *prytanis* (who held the kingly position for his brief term), probably a council (though none is specifically documented in the scant literary materials), and a *polemarchos* to head the army.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] During Bacchiad rule from 747 to 650 BC, Corinth became a unified state.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Large scale public buildings and monuments were constructed at this time.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 733 BC, Corinth established colonies at Corcyra and Syracuse.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] By 730 BC, Corinth emerged as a highly advanced Greek city with at least 5,000 people.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Aristotle tells the story of Philolaus of Corinth, a Bacchiad who was a lawgiver at Thebes.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] He became the lover of Diocles, the winner of the Olympic games.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] They both lived for the rest of their lives in Thebes.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Their tombs were built near one another and Philolaus' tomb points toward the Corinthian country, while Diocles' faces away.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 657 BC, polemarch Cypselus obtained an oracle from Delphi which he interpreted to mean that he should rule the city.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] He seized power and exiled the Bacchiadae.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Cypselus (Κύψελος, *Kýpselos*) was the first tyrant of Corinth in the 7th century BC.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] From 658–628 BC, he removed the Bacchiad aristocracy from power and ruled for three decades.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] He built temples to Apollo and Poseidon in 650 BC.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Cypselus was the son of Eëtion and a disfigured woman named Labda.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] He was a member of the Bacchiad kin and usurped the power in archaic matriarchal right of his mother.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] According to Herodotus, the Bacchiadae heard two prophecies from the Delphic oracle that the son of Eëtion would overthrow their dynasty, and they planned to kill the baby once he was born.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] However, the newborn smiled at each of the men sent to kill him, and none of them could bear to strike the blow.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Labda then hid the baby in a chest, and the men could not find him once they had composed themselves and returned to kill him.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] (Compare the infancy of Perseus.) The ivory chest of Cypselus was richly worked and adorned with gold.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] It was a votive offering at Olympia, where Pausanias gave it a minute description in his 2nd century AD travel guide.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Cypselus grew up and fulfilled the prophecy.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Corinth had been involved in wars with Argos and Corcyra, and the Corinthians were unhappy with their rulers.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Cypselus was polemarch at the time (around 657 BC), the archon in charge of the military, and he used his influence with the soldiers to expel the king.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] He also expelled his other enemies, but allowed them to set up colonies in northwestern Greece.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] He also increased trade with the colonies in Italy and Sicily.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] He was a popular ruler and, unlike many later tyrants, he did not need a bodyguard and died a natural death.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Aristotle reports that "Cypselus of Corinth had made a vow that if he became master of the city, he would offer to Zeus the entire property of the Corinthians.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The city sent forth colonists to found new settlements in the 7th century BC, under the rule of Cypselus (r.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Those settlements were Epidamnus (modern day Durrës, Albania), Syracuse, Ambracia, Corcyra (modern day town of Corfu), and Anactorium.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Periander also founded Apollonia in Illyria (modern day Fier, Albania) and Potidaea (in Chalcidice).
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Corinth was also one of the nine Greek sponsor-cities to found the colony of Naukratis in Ancient Egypt, founded to accommodate the increasing trade volume between the Greek world and pharaonic Egypt during the reign of Pharaoh Psammetichus I of the 26th Dynasty.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] He ruled for thirty years and was succeeded as tyrant by his son Periander in 627 BC.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The treasury that Cypselus built at Delphi was apparently still standing in the time of Herodotus, and the chest of Cypselus was seen by Pausanias at Olympia in the 2nd century AD.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Periander brought Corcyra to order in 600 BC.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Periander was considered one of the Seven Wise Men of Greece.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] During his reign, the first Corinthian coins were struck.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] He was the first to attempt to cut across the Isthmus to create a seaway between the Corinthian and the Saronic Gulfs.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] He abandoned the venture due to the extreme technical difficulties that he met, but he created the Diolkos instead (a stone-built overland ramp).
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The era of the Cypselids was Corinth's golden age, and ended with Periander's nephew Psammetichus (Corinthian tyrant), named after the hellenophile Egyptian Pharaoh Psammetichus I (see above).
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] His son Lycophron found out and shunned him, and Periander exiled the son to Corcyra.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Periander later wanted Lycophron to replace him as ruler of Corinth, and convinced him to come home to Corinth on the condition that Periander go to Corcyra.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Corcyreans heard about this and killed Lycophron to keep away Periander.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] 581 BC: Periander's nephew and successor was assassinated, ending the tyranny.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] 581 BC: the Isthmian Games were established by leading families.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] 570 BC: the inhabitants started to use silver coins called 'colts' or 'foals'.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] 550 BC: Construction of the Temple of Apollo at Corinth (early third quarter of the 6th century BC).
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] 525 BC: Corinth formed a conciliatory alliance with Sparta against Argos.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] 519 BC: Corinth mediated between Athens and Thebes.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Around 500 BC: Athenians and Corinthians entreated Spartans not to harm Athens by restoring the tyrant.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Just before the classical period, according to Thucydides, the Corinthians developed the trireme which became the standard warship of the Mediterranean until the late Roman period.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Corinth fought the first naval battle on record against the Hellenic city of Corcyra.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Corinthians were also known for their wealth due to their strategic location on the isthmus, through which all land traffic had to pass en route to the Peloponnese, including messengers and traders.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In classical times, Corinth rivaled Athens and Thebes in wealth, based on the Isthmian traffic and trade.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Until the mid-6th century, Corinth was a major exporter of black-figure pottery to city-states around the Greek world, later losing their market to Athenian artisans.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In classical times and earlier, Corinth had a temple of Aphrodite, the goddess of love, employing some thousand hetairas (temple prostitutes) (see also Temple prostitution in Corinth).
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The city was renowned for these temple prostitutes, who served the wealthy merchants and the powerful officials who frequented the city.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Lais, the most famous hetaira, was said to charge tremendous fees for her extraordinary favours.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Referring to the city's exorbitant luxuries, Horace is quoted as saying: "*non licet omnibus adire Corinthum*" ("not everyone is able to go to Corinth").
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Corinth was also the host of the Isthmian Games.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] During this era, Corinthians developed the Corinthian order, the third main style of classical architecture after the Doric and the Ionic.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The city had two main ports: to the west on the Corinthian Gulf lay Lechaion, which connected the city to its western colonies (Greek: apoikiai) and Magna Graecia, while to the east on the Saronic Gulf the port of Kenchreai served the ships coming from Athens, Ionia, Cyprus and the Levant.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Both ports had docks for the city's large navy.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 491 BC, Corinth mediated between Syracuse and Gela in Sicily.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] During the years 481–480 BC, the Conference at the Isthmus of Corinth (following conferences at Sparta) established the Hellenic League, which allied under the Spartans to fight the war against Persia.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The city was a major participant in the Persian Wars, sending 400 soldiers to defend Thermopylae and supplying forty warships for the Battle of Salamis under Adeimantos and 5,000 hoplites with their characteristic Corinthian helmets) in the following Battle of Plataea.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Greeks obtained the surrender of Theban collaborators with the Persians.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Pausanias took them to Corinth where they were put to death.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Following the Battle of Thermopylae and the subsequent Battle of Artemisium, which resulted in the captures of Euboea, Boeotia, and Attica, the Greco-Persian Wars were at a point where now most of mainland Greece to the north of the Isthmus of Corinth had been overrun.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Herodotus, who was believed to dislike the Corinthians, mentions that they were considered the second best fighters after the Athenians.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 458 BC, Corinth was defeated by Athens at Megara.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 435 BC, Corinth and its colony Corcyra went to war over Epidamnus.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 433 BC, Athens allied with Corcyra against Corinth.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Corinthian war against the Corcyrans was the largest naval battle between Greek city states until that time.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 431 BC, one of the factors leading to the Peloponnesian War was the dispute between Corinth and Athens over Corcyra, which possibly stemmed from the traditional trade rivalry between the two cities or, as Thucydides relates – the dispute over the colony of Epidamnus.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Syracusans sent envoys to Corinth and Sparta to seek allies against Athenian invasion.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Corinthians "voted at once to aid [the Syracusans] heart and soul".
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Corinthians also sent a group to Lacedaemon to rouse Spartan assistance.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] After a convincing speech from the Athenian renegade Alcibiades, the Spartans agreed to send troops to aid the Sicilians.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 404 BC, Sparta refused to destroy Athens, angering the Corinthians.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Corinth joined Argos, Boeotia, and Athens against Sparta in the Corinthian War.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Demosthenes later used this history in a plea for magnanimous statecraft, noting that the Athenians of yesteryear had had good reason to hate the Corinthians and Thebans for their conduct during the Peloponnesian War, yet they bore no malice whatever.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 395 BC, after the end of the Peloponnesian War, Corinth and Thebes, dissatisfied with the hegemony of their Spartan allies, moved to support Athens against Sparta in the Corinthian War.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] As an example of facing danger with knowledge, Aristotle used the example of the Argives who were forced to confront the Spartans in the battle at the Long Walls of Corinth in 392 BC.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 379 BC, Corinth, switching back to the Peloponnesian League, joined Sparta in an attempt to defeat Thebes and eventually take over Athens.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 366 BC, the Athenian Assembly ordered Chares to occupy the Athenian ally and install a democratic government.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] This failed when Corinth, Phlius and Epidaurus allied with Boeotia.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Demosthenes recounts how Athens had fought the Spartans in a great battle near Corinth.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The city decided not to harbor the defeated Athenian troops, but instead sent heralds to the Spartans.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] But the Corinthian heralds opened their gates to the defeated Athenians and saved them.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] These conflicts further weakened the city-states of the Peloponnese and set the stage for the conquests of Philip II of Macedon.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Demosthenes warned that Philip's military force exceeded that of Athens and thus they must develop a tactical advantage.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] He noted the importance of a citizen army as opposed to a mercenary force, citing the mercenaries of Corinth who fought alongside citizens and defeated the Spartans.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 338 BC, after having defeated Athens and its allies, Philip II created the League of Corinth to unite Greece (included Corinth and Macedonia) in the war against Persia.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In the spring of 337 BC, the Second congress of Corinth established the Common Peace.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] By 332 BC, Alexander the Great was in control of Greece, as hegemon.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] During the Hellenistic period, Corinth, like many other Greece cities, never quite had autonomy.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Under the successors of Alexander the Great, Greece was contested ground, and Corinth was occasionally the battleground for contests between the Antigonids, based in Macedonia, and other Hellenistic powers.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 308 BC, the city was captured from the Antigonids by Ptolemy I, who claimed to come as a liberator of Greece from the Antigonids.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] However, the city was recaptured by Demetrius in 304 BC.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Corinth remained under Antigonid control for half a century.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] After 280 BC, it was ruled by the faithful governor Craterus; but, in 253/2 BC, his son Alexander of Corinth, moved by Ptolemaic subsidies, resolved to challenge the Macedonian supremacy and seek independence as a tyrant.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] He was probably poisoned in 247 BC; after his death, the Macedonian king Antigonus II Gonatas retook the city in the winter of 245/44 BC.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 243 BC, Aratus of Sicyon, using a surprise attack, captured the fortress of Acrocorinth and convinced the citizenship to join the Achaean League.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Thanks to an alliance agreement with Aratus, the Macedonians recovered Corinth once again in 224 BC; but, after the Roman intervention in 197 BC, the city was permanently brought into the Achaean League.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Under the leadership of Philopoemen, the Achaeans went on to take control of the entire Peloponnesus and made Corinth the capital of their confederation.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 146 BC, Rome declared war on the Achaean League.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] A series of Roman victories culminated in the Battle of Corinth, after which the army of Lucius Mummius besieged, captured, and burned the city.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Mummius killed all the men and sold the women and children into slavery; he was subsequently given the cognomen *Achaicus* as the conqueror of the Achaean League.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] There is archeological evidence of some minimal habitation in the years afterwards, but Corinth remained largely deserted until Julius Caesar refounded the city as *Colonia Laus Iulia Corinthiensis* ("colony of Corinth in honour of Julius") in 44 BC, shortly before his assassination.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Under the Romans, Corinth was rebuilt as a major city in Southern Greece or Achaia.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] It had a large mixed population of Romans, Greeks, and Jews.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The city was an important locus for activities of The Roman Imperial Cult, and both Temple E and the Julian Basilica have been suggested as locations of imperial cult activity.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Corinth is mentioned many times in the New Testament, largely in connection with Paul the Apostle's mission there, testifying to the success of Caesar's refounding of the city.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Traditionally, the Church of Corinth is believed to have been founded by Paul, making it an Apostolic See.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The apostle Paul first visited the city in AD 49 or 50, when Gallio, the brother of Seneca, was proconsul of Achaia.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Paul resided here for eighteen months (see Acts 18:11).
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Here he first became acquainted with Priscilla and Aquila, with whom he later traveled.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] They worked here together as tentmakers (from which is derived the modern Christian concept of tentmaking), and regularly attended the synagogue.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In AD 51/52, Gallio presided over the trial of the Apostle Paul in Corinth.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Silas and Timothy rejoined Paul here, having last seen him in Berea (Acts 18:5).
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Acts 18:6 suggests that Jewish refusal to accept his preaching here led Paul to resolve no longer to speak in the synagogues where he travelled: "From now on I will go to the Gentiles".
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] However, on his arrival in Ephesus (Acts 18:19), the narrative records that Paul went to the synagogue to preach.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Paul wrote at least two epistles to the Christian church, the First Epistle to the Corinthians (written from Ephesus) and the Second Epistle to the Corinthians (written from Macedonia).
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Both canonical epistles occasionally reflect the conflict between the missionary ambitions of the thriving Christian church and a strong desire to remain separate from the surrounding community.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Some scholars believe that Paul visited Corinth for an intermediate "painful visit" (see 2 Corinthians 2:1) between the first and second epistles.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] After writing the second epistle, he stayed in Corinth for about three months in the late winter, and there wrote his Epistle to the Romans.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Based on clues within the Corinthian epistles themselves, some scholars have concluded that Paul wrote possibly as many as four epistles to the church at Corinth.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Only two are contained within the Christian canon (First and Second Epistles to the Corinthians); the other two letters are lost.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] This letter is not to be confused with the so-called "Third Epistle to the Corinthians", which is a pseudepigraphical letter written many years after the death of Paul.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] There are speculations from Bruce Winter that the Jewish access to their own food in Corinth was disallowed after Paul's departure.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] By this theory, Paul had instructed Christian Gentiles to maintain Jewish access to food according to their dietary laws.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] This speculation is contested by David Rudolph, who argues that there is no evidence to support this theory.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] He argues instead that Paul had desired the Gentile Christians to remain assimilated within their Gentile communities and not adopt Jewish dietary procedures.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The city was largely destroyed in the earthquakes of AD 365 and AD 375, followed by Alaric's invasion in 396.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The city was rebuilt after these disasters on a monumental scale, but covered a much smaller area than previously.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Four churches were located in the city proper, another on the citadel of the Acrocorinth, and a monumental basilica at the port of Lechaion.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] During the reign of Emperor Justinian I (527–565), a large stone wall was erected from the Saronic to the Corinthian gulfs, protecting the city and the Peloponnese peninsula from the barbarian invasions from the north.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The stone wall was about six miles (10 km) long and was named Hexamilion ("six-miles").
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In the end of the 6th century a group of Slavs raided Corinth.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Their chieftain looted a ciborium from a church, which he then used as a tent and living space.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The city continued to decline, and may even have fallen to barbarian invaders in the early 7th century.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The main settlement moved from the lower city to the Acrocorinth.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Despite its becoming the capital of the theme of Hellas and, after c.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] 800, of the theme of the Peloponnese, it was not until the 9th century that the city began to recover, reaching its apogee in the 11th and 12th centuries, when it was the site of a flourishing silk industry.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In November 856, an earthquake in Corinth killed an estimated 45,000.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The wealth of the city attracted the attention of the Italo-Normans under Roger II of Sicily, who plundered it in 1147, carrying off many captives, most notably silk weavers.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The city never fully recovered from the Norman sack.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Following the sack of Constantinople by the Fourth Crusade, a group of Crusaders under the French knights William of Champlitte and Geoffrey of Villehardouin carried out the conquest of the Peloponnese.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Corinthians resisted the Frankish conquest from their stronghold in Acrocorinth, under the command of Leo Sgouros, from 1205 until 1210.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 1208 Leo Sgouros killed himself by riding off the top of Acrocorinth, but resistance continued for two more years.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Finally, in 1210 the fortress fell to the Crusaders, and Corinth became a full part of the Principality of Achaea, governed by the Villehardouins from their capital in Andravida in Elis.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Corinth was the last significant town of Achaea on its northern borders with another crusader state, the Duchy of Athens.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Byzantines of the Despotate of the Morea recaptured it in 1403, and the Despot Theodore II Palaiologos, restored the Hexamilion wall across the Isthmus of Corinth in 1415.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 1458, five years after the final Fall of Constantinople, the Turks of the Ottoman Empire conquered the city and its mighty castle.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Ottomans renamed it *Gördüs* (گوردوس) and made it a *sanjak* (district) centre within the Rumelia Eyalet.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Venetians captured the city in 1687 during the Morean War, and it remained under Venetian control until the Ottomans retook the city in 1715.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Corinth was the capital of the Mora Eyalet in 1715–1731 and then again a *sanjak* capital until 1821.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] During the Greek War of Independence, 1821–1830 the city was contested by the Ottoman forces.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] At that time, the Arvanite tribes living to the north of the Isthmus of Corinth attacked the acropolis of the city.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] They were around 2000 musketeers against the Ottoman troops.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The city was officially liberated in 1832 after the Treaty of London.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 1833, the site was considered among the candidates for the new capital city of the recently founded Kingdom of Greece, due to its historical significance and strategic position.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Nafplio was chosen initially, then Athens.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The Acrocorinth (Ἀκροκόρινθος, *Akrokórinthos*), the acropolis of ancient Corinth, is a monolithic rock that was continuously occupied from archaic times to the early 19th century.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The city's archaic acropolis, already an easily defensible position due to its geomorphology, was further heavily fortified during the Byzantine Empire as it became the seat of the strategos of the Thema of Hellas.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Later it was a fortress of the Franks after the Fourth Crusade, the Venetians and the Ottoman Turks.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] With its secure water supply, Acrocorinth's fortress was used as the last line of defense in southern Greece because it commanded the isthmus of Corinth, repelling foes from entry into the Peloponnesian peninsula.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Three circuit walls formed the man-made defense of the hill.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The highest peak on the site was home to a temple to Aphrodite which was Christianized as a church, and then became a mosque.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The American School began excavations on it in 1929.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Currently, Acrocorinth is one of the most important medieval castle sites of Greece.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Corinth had two harbours: Lechaeum on the Corinthian Gulf and Cenchreae on the Saronic Gulf.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Lechaeum was the principal port, connected to the city with a set of long walls of about 3 kilometres (1.9 mi) length, and was the main trading station for Italy and Sicily, where there were many Corinthian colonies, while Cenchreae served the commerce with the Eastern Mediterranean.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Ships could be transported between the two harbours by means of the diolkos constructed by the tyrant Periander.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] The **Corinth Excavations** by the American School of Classical Studies at Athens began in 1896 and have continued with little interruption until today.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Restricted by the modern village of Ancient Corinth, which directly overlies the ancient city, the main focus of School investigations has been on the area surrounding the mid-6th century B.C.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] This dominating monument has been one of the only features of the site visible since antiquity.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Archaeologists such as Bert Hodge Hill, Carl Blegen, William Dinsmoor Sr., Oscar Broneer, and Rhys Carpenter worked to uncover much of the site before WWII.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Since then, under the leadership of directors Henry Robinson (1959–1965), Charles K.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Sanders (1997–present), excavation has clarified the archaeological history of the city.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Investigations have revealed remains extending from the Early Neolithic period (6500-5750 B.C.) through to early modern times.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Archaeological work has also been done outside the immediate area of the village center including at the Sanctuary of Demeter and Kore on the slopes of Acrocorinth, in the Potters’ Quarter, at the sites of the Sanctuary of Asklepios and the Kenchreian Gate Basilica.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Current investigations focus on the area of the Panayia Field, located to the southeast of the Forum.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] School excavations and projects affiliated to the ASCSA have also intensively explored the wider area of the Corinthia including the surrounding settlements of Korakou, Kenchreai and Isthmia.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] Finds from these works are housed in the Archaeological Museum of Ancient Corinth.
[src:actium/ancient-corinth] In 1858, the village surrounding the ruins of Ancient Corinth was destroyed by an earthquake, leading to the establishment of New Corinth 3 km (1.9 mi) north east of the ancient city.
